## Disabling the regression trip-wire

The trip-wire is on by default and catches catastrophic outputs (empty file,
NaN/error tokens, runtime > 10× baseline, structurally invalid). To disable it,
edit the `TRIP_WIRE_ENABLED` constant near the top of `scorer.py` from `True`
to `False`. **Disabling is not recommended for unattended overnight loops** —
the trip-wire is the main defense against the agent discovering degenerate
shortcuts that score well on the other criteria.

## Setting the trip-wire's runtime baseline

After your first successful run completes, write the wall-clock time (in
seconds) into a file at `$$RUBRIC_OUTPUTS_DIR/runtime_seconds.txt`, and update
the `BASELINE_RUNTIME_SECONDS` constant in `scorer.py` from `None` to that
value. Subsequent runs that exceed 10× the baseline will fail the
`runtime_exceeded` trip-wire check. This catches indicator code that
inadvertently goes into an infinite loop — a common failure mode for
unattended optimization runs.

## What `scorer.py` expects in `$$RUBRIC_OUTPUTS_DIR`

**Deterministic mode:** your `run_command` must write `scores.json` with a
`{criterion_name: float}` mapping. The scorer reads it, validates each entry,
and aggregates into the composite.

**LLM-judge mode:** your `run_command` must write the main output artifact
(default: `${main_output_filename}`). The scorer calls an LLM N=3 times per
criterion (temperature=0, seed=42) and averages. Set environment variables
`RUBRIC_LLM_ENDPOINT` and `RUBRIC_LLM_API_KEY` before running.
